{"title_page": "2020 Suncorp Super Netball season", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title            = 2020 Suncorp Super Netball season\n| league           = [[Suncorp Super Netball]]\n| sport            = [[Netball]]\n| logo             = File:Suncorp-super-netball-logo.png\n| pixels           = \n| caption          = \n| duration         = Season has been suspended\n| no_of_teams      = 8\n| attendance       = \n| TV               = [[Nine Network]]\n| top_pick         = \n| picked_by        = \n| season           = Regular season\n| minor_premiers   = \n| MVP              = \n| MVP_link         = \n| top_scorer       = \n| top_scorer_link  = \n| playoffs         = \n| playoffs_link    = \n| playoffs_MVP_link= \n| finals           = Finals\n| finals_link      = \n| finals_champ     = \n| finals_runner-up = \n| finals_MVP       = \n| finals_MVP_link  = \n| seasonslist      =  \n| seasonslistnames = \n| prevseason_link  = 2019 Suncorp Super Netball season\n| prevseason_year  = 2019\n| nextseason_link  = 2021 Suncorp Super Netball season\n| nextseason_year  = 2021\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 [[Suncorp Super Netball]] season''' will be the fourth season of the premier [[Netball in Australia|netball]] league in [[Australia]]. The season was to begin on 2 May, though has been suspended to at least 30 June as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://supernetball.com.au/news/2020-suncorp-super-netball-fixture-revealed|title=2020 Suncorp Super Netball fixture released|work=Super Netball|date=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://supernetball.com.au/news/suncorp-super-netball-2020-season-hold|title=Suncorp Super Netball 2020 Season on Hold|work=Super Netball|date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The defending premiers are the [[New South Wales Swifts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/15/swifts-thrash-lightning-in-super-netball-grand-final-|title=Swifts thrash Lightning in Super Netball grand final|work=The Guardian|date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n===Teams===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Captain/s <small>(subject to change)</small>\n! Coach \n! Home Courts\n! Ref.\n|-\n| [[File:ANZ Thunderbirds.svg|15px]] '''[[Adelaide Thunderbirds]]'''\n| [[Chelsea Pitman]] &<br>[[Layla Guscoth]]\n| Tania Obst\n| [[Priceline Stadium]]<br>[[Adelaide Entertainment Centre]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:SSN Magpies.png|15px]] '''[[Collingwood Magpies Netball|Collingwood Magpies]]'''\n| [[Madison Browne]] &<br>[[Geva Mentor]]\n| Rob Wright\n| [[Melbourne Arena]]<br>[[State Netball and Hockey Centre]]<br>[[Silverdome (Launceston)|Silverdome]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:SSN Giants.png|15px]] '''[[Giants Netball]]'''\n| [[Jo Harten]]\n| Julie Fitzgerald\n| [[Sydney Olympic Park Tennis Centre|Ken Rosewall Arena]]<br>[[AIS Arena]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:ANZ Vixens.svg|15px]] '''[[Melbourne Vixens]]'''\n| [[Kate Moloney]]\n| [[Simone McKinnis]]\n| [[Melbourne Arena]]<br>[[Margaret Court Arena]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:ANZ Swifts.svg|15px]] '''[[New South Wales Swifts]]'''\n| [[Maddy Proud]]\n| Briony Akle\n| [[Sydney Olympic Park Tennis Centre|Ken Rosewall Arena]]\n| \n|-   \n| [[File:ANZ Firebirds.svg|15px]] '''[[Queensland Firebirds]]''' \n| [[Gabi Simpson]]\n| Roselee Jenke   \n| [[Queensland State Netball Centre|Nissan Arena]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:SSN Lightning.png|15px]] '''[[Sunshine Coast Lightning]]'''\n| [[Laura Langman]]\n| Kylee Byrne\n| [[University of the Sunshine Coast#Netball stadium|University of Sunshine Coast Stadium]]\n| \n|-\n| [[File:ANZ Fever.svg|15px]] '''[[West Coast Fever]]'''\n| [[Courtney Bruce]]\n| [[Stacey Marinkovich]]\n| [[RAC Arena (Perth)|RAC Arena]]\n| \n|}\n\n===Format===\nThe season is played over fourteen rounds, allowing every team to play each other twice, once at home and once away. The top four teams on the [[Standings|ladder]] at the conclusion of the [[Season (sports)#Regular season|regular season]] qualify for the [[Playoffs|finals series]]. In the first week of the finals series, the 1st ranked team hosts the 2nd ranked team in the major semi-final (with the winner of that match to qualify for the [[Grand Final]]) and the 3rd ranked team hosts the 4th ranked team in the minor semi-final (with the loser of that match eliminated). The loser of the major semi-final then hosts the winner of the minor semi-final in the preliminary final. The winner of the major semi-final then hosts the winner of the preliminary final in the Grand Final.\n\n===Rule changes===\nThe Super Netball commission announced changes to the league structure in February. Rolling [[Substitution (sport)|substitutions]] during play will be permitted, as well as during stoppages and intervals, with no limit to the number of substitutions that can be made, and multiple substitutions allowed to be made at any one time. The substitute must tag hands with the player leaving the court before entering the field of play. Extra time in the event of draws will be introduced, after six matches were tied throughout the [[2019 Suncorp Super Netball season|previous season]]. The match will enter one 5-minute period of extra time. If at the end of this period teams remain tied, the match will be declared a draw. If a team has a one-goal or greater advantage at the end of the period, they will be declared the winner. The bonus point system in place for the past two seasons will remain, though no bonus points will be awarded for goals scored in extra time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://supernetball.com.au/news/suncorp-super-netball-rule-changes|title=Suncorp Super Netball Rule Changes|work=Super Netball|date=7 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/6619737/harten-backs-extra-time-in-super-netball/?cs=2512|title=Harten backs extra time in Super Netball|date=6 February 2020|work=Bendigo Advertiser}}</ref>\n\n==Player transfers==\nThe league unveiled the list of non-contracted athletes on 14 August 2019, two weeks before that season's finals series were scheduled to commence.<ref name=firstlist>{{cite web|url=https://supernetball.com.au/news/suncorp-super-netball-releases-list-uncontracted-players|work=Super Netball|date=14 August 2019|title=Suncorp Super Netball Releases List Of Uncontracted Players|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815081204/https://supernetball.com.au/news/suncorp-super-netball-releases-list-uncontracted-players|archivedate=15 August 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> Teams had the exclusive right to re-sign any of their existing contracted players, their permanent/temporary replacement players or training partners, on single year or multi-year contracts for the 2020 and 2021 seasons. Contracts with players from other teams and leagues could not be announced until the signing period commenced on 16 September 2019. This period closed on 14 October 2019, upon which teams were required to have submitted their 10 senior-listed players for the 2020 season. Training partners could be signed by clubs at any time.<ref name=firstlist/>\n\n===Signings===\nThe following table is a list of players who moved clubs/leagues into Super Netball, or were elevated into a permanent position in the senior team, during the off-season. It does not include players who were re-signed by their original Super Netball clubs.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:78%; text-align:center; text-align:left;\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Moving from\n!Moving to\n!Ref\n|-\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Maddie Hay]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Giants Netball]] ([[Australian Netball League|ANL]]; training partner)\n|[[File:SSN Giants.png|15px]] [[Giants Netball]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.giantsnetball.com.au/maddie-hay-signs-for-2020/|title=Maddy Hay signs for 2020|date=6 September 2019|work=Giants Netball}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Molly Jovic]]\u2020\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Collingwood Magpies#Tasmanian Magpies|Tasmanian Magpies]] (